---
import CalculatorLayout from '@layouts/CalculatorLayout.astro';
import { SavingsGoalCalc } from '@components/calculators/SavingsGoalCalc';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'How much should I save each month?',
    answer:
      'The common guideline is 20% of your income (from the 50/30/20 rule), but the right amount depends on your specific goal, timeline, and circumstances. Use this calculator to find the exact monthly amount needed for your target. For freelancers with variable income, save more during good months to build a buffer for lean periods.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What interest rate should I use?',
    answer:
      'It depends on where you keep your savings. High-yield savings accounts currently offer 4-5% APY. CDs might offer slightly more for locked-in terms. Index fund investments historically return 7-10% annually but with volatility. For short-term goals (under 2 years), use your HYSA rate. For longer goals, a conservative 6-7% for diversified investments is reasonable.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I account for inflation?',
    answer:
      'Yes, for goals more than 2-3 years away. Inflation (historically ~3% in the US) erodes purchasing power over time. A $50,000 goal in 10 years will actually need about $67,000 in future dollars to have the same purchasing power. Use advanced mode to add inflation adjustment to your target.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is an irregular income buffer?',
    answer:
      'Freelancers and gig workers don\'t earn the same amount every month. An irregular income buffer (10-20% extra) accounts for lean months when you might not be able to save the full target amount. By saving more during good months, you stay on track even when income dips. This is one of the most important adjustments for self-employed savers.',
  },
];

const relatedCalculators = [
  {
    name: 'FIRE Calculator',
    description: 'Plan your path to financial independence with savings rate projections',
    href: '/personal-finance/fire-calculator',
    category: 'Personal Finance',
  },
  {
    name: 'Emergency Fund Calculator',
    description: 'Calculate how much you need for a financial safety net',
    href: '/personal-finance/emergency-fund-calculator',
    category: 'Personal Finance',
  },
  {
    name: 'Net Worth Calculator',
    description: 'Track all your assets and liabilities in one place',
    href: '/personal-finance/net-worth-calculator',
    category: 'Personal Finance',
  },
  {
    name: 'Side Hustle Time to Goal Calculator',
    description: 'See how side income accelerates your savings timeline',
    href: '/side-hustle/time-to-goal-calculator',
    category: 'Side Hustle',
  },
];
---

<CalculatorLayout
  title="Savings Goal Calculator - Monthly Savings Planner | CalcFalcon"
  description="Calculate how much to save monthly to reach your financial goal. See interest projections, inflation adjustments, and irregular income buffers. Free savings goal calculator."
  calculatorName="Savings Goal Calculator"
  category="Personal Finance"
  categorySlug="personal-finance"
  slug="savings-goal-calculator"
  faqs={faqs}
  relatedCalculators={relatedCalculators}
  ogImage="/og-images/savings-goal.png"
>
  <Fragment slot="intro">
    <section class="mb-8">
      <div class="prose prose-neutral max-w-none">
        <h2>Setting a Savings Goal: The Math Behind Reaching Your Target</h2>
        <p>Whether you are saving for a down payment, an emergency fund, a business investment, or a major purchase, the fundamental question is the same: how much do you need to set aside each month to reach your target by your deadline? The answer depends on your starting balance, your timeline, and the interest rate your savings earn along the way.</p>
        <p>Compound interest works in your favor here. Money saved in a high-yield savings account or invested in a diversified portfolio earns returns that themselves earn returns. Over longer time horizons, this compounding effect becomes substantial — a meaningful portion of your final balance comes from interest earned, not money you personally deposited. The earlier you start, the more compounding does the heavy lifting.</p>
        <h3>How This Calculator Plans Your Path</h3>
        <p>Enter your goal amount, current savings, expected interest rate, and timeline. The calculator determines the exact monthly contribution needed and projects your savings growth month by month. The chart shows a clear visual of your progress toward the goal line. For freelancers, Advanced mode adds an irregular income buffer — an extra percentage on top of the required savings to account for months when variable income might make the full contribution difficult.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </Fragment>

  <SavingsGoalCalc client:visible />
  <Fragment slot="content">
    <section class="mb-10">
      <div class="prose prose-neutral max-w-none">
        <h2>How to Use the Savings Goal Calculator</h2>
        <p>Enter your savings target, current balance, timeline, and interest rate to see exactly how much you need to save each month. The projection chart shows your savings growth toward the goal line.</p>
        <h3>Quick Mode</h3>
        <p>Set your target amount, current savings, monthly contribution, interest rate, and timeline. The calculator shows your required monthly savings, time to goal, total contributions, and interest earned from compounding.</p>
        <h3>Advanced Mode</h3>
        <p>Add inflation adjustment to ensure your target maintains purchasing power over time. The irregular income buffer adds a percentage on top of required savings — essential for freelancers whose monthly income varies. This ensures you stay on track even during lean months.</p>
        <h3>Built for Freelancers</h3>
        <p>Unlike generic savings calculators, this one accounts for the reality of self-employment: variable income, no employer match, and the need to be your own financial planner. The irregular income buffer feature helps you plan realistically instead of optimistically.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="deep-dive">
    <section class="mb-10">
      <div class="prose prose-neutral max-w-none">
        <h2>How Compound Interest Accelerates Your Savings</h2>
        <p>The table below shows how a $500 monthly contribution grows at different interest rates over various time horizons. The difference between a standard savings account and an invested portfolio becomes dramatic over longer periods.</p>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Years</th><th>0% (Mattress)</th><th>2% (Savings)</th><th>5% (HYSA/CDs)</th><th>7% (Invested)</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>3</td><td>$18,000</td><td>$18,545</td><td>$19,375</td><td>$19,945</td></tr>
            <tr><td>5</td><td>$30,000</td><td>$31,530</td><td>$34,035</td><td>$35,795</td></tr>
            <tr><td>10</td><td>$60,000</td><td>$66,360</td><td>$77,640</td><td>$86,540</td></tr>
            <tr><td>15</td><td>$90,000</td><td>$104,640</td><td>$133,280</td><td>$158,380</td></tr>
            <tr><td>20</td><td>$120,000</td><td>$147,000</td><td>$205,520</td><td>$260,480</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>At 7 percent over 20 years, more than half of the final balance ($140,480) comes from compounding returns rather than your own deposits. This is why where you keep your savings matters almost as much as how much you save.</p>
        <h2>Choosing the Right Savings Vehicle</h2>
        <p><strong>Short-term goals (under 2 years):</strong> High-yield savings account. Your money needs to be accessible and stable. Current HYSAs offer 4 to 5 percent with no volatility risk. Do not invest short-term savings in the stock market — a downturn right before you need the money could force you to sell at a loss.</p>
        <p><strong>Medium-term goals (2 to 5 years):</strong> A mix of HYSA and short-term bond funds. CDs can lock in today's rates if you believe rates will fall. The key is balancing some growth potential against the risk of needing the money before markets recover from a dip.</p>
        <p><strong>Long-term goals (5+ years):</strong> Diversified index fund portfolio. Over longer horizons, the stock market's historical 7 to 10 percent annual return significantly outpaces savings accounts. The longer your timeline, the more time markets have to recover from temporary declines.</p>
        <h2>Saving on a Freelance Income</h2>
        <p>Variable income makes consistent saving challenging but not impossible. The irregular income buffer in this calculator adds a percentage cushion to your required monthly savings, ensuring you stay on track even when income dips. During high-earning months, save more than the target to build a buffer for leaner months. Many freelancers find it helpful to maintain a separate operating account with two to three months of expenses as a cash flow buffer, independent of their savings goals. This prevents the common pattern of raiding long-term savings to cover short-term cash flow gaps.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </Fragment>
</CalculatorLayout>
